			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">For untrusted hardware exception handling on Windows we are using the Windows debug API to catch exceptions.  However, there is a runtime cost associated with having a debugger process attached to sel_ldr, because every time sel_ldr creates or destroys a thread, the sel_ldr process is suspended.

We should change it so that the debugger process is only started and attached when untrusted code registers an exception handler, so that apps only pay the cost for this feature when they are using it.
